**Introduction**

Kaggle.com posted a 66.3 MB (megabyte) file showing credit card fraud data. The data:

Reports transactions "made by credit cards in September 2013 by European cardholders."

The data contains 492 frauds out of 284,807 transactions (~ 0.172% of the total)

The data has been anonymized, but the label (fraud or genuine) and amounts are accurate.

The data is highly imbalanced, so Area Under the Curve is an appropriate measure. Accuracy measures are not meaningful for highly imbalanced data sets such as this one.

The data set contains 284,807 rows, and 31 variables. It is 66.3 MB in size.

The data is transformed by Principal Components Analysis, due to confidentiality of the original data.

The target column, Class, only has values of 1 (fraud) or 0 (no fraud).

The LogisticEnsembles package was used to analyze the data. The results of the analysis:

Eight individual models and four ensembles of models were automatically constructed from the data.

A seed was set (12345) to ensure the results are fully reproducible.

One of the individual models and three of the ensembles achieved 100% accuracy as measured by the AUC curves on the holdout data.

The NumericEnsembles package also automatically provided nine reports and 32 graphs and plots, allowing a complete description and analysis of the data and the recommended solutions.

Based on the analysis, the following are recommended:

Four of the logistic models, (XGBoost, Ensemble C50, Ensemble Elastic and Ensemble XGBoost) achieved 100% scores on AUC, Sensitivity, Specificity, Positive Predictive Value, Negative Predictive Value, and F1 Score. They also achieved 0% on False Positive and False Negative tests. These are the models which are most likely to provide accurate predictions from the data.

Statement of the problem from the customer’s perspective

According to a paper from the European Central Bank report on payment fraud dated 15 December, 2025, "In 2024 payment fraud rate in European Economic Area stable at around 0.002% of total value of transactions in a calendar year." This amounted to a total of €4.2 billion in 2024, which is an increase from € 3.5 billion in 2023 and € 3.4 billion in 2022.

The report breaks down the numbers as follows:

For 2024, the overall losses for credit transfers were €2.200 billion (a year-on-year increase of 16%), and for card payments with cards issued in the EU/EEA they were €1.329 billion (a year-on-year increase of 29%). For credit transfers, payment service users bore approximately 85% of total fraud losses in 2024, mainly as a result of scams that tricked users into initiating fraudulent transactions.

FICO posted on a blog post, How Is Credit Card Fraud Changing in Europe? which is based on data from Euromonitor International showed that credit card fraud is steadily rising. According to the report,

Key countries driving the overall increase since 2021 are:

Norway, where fraud losses have dramatically increased from €14M to €26.4M

Denmark, with a more than twofold increase in fraud losses (€19.6M to €47.6M)

Hungary, which has jumped from €3.3M to €22.4M

Greece, with a twofold increase from €13.4M to €28.4M

Sweden, where losses have risen from €13.1M to €24.2M, an increase of around 85%.

The FICO report discusses what credit card issuers can do to fight fraud, and conclude with these recommendations:

Fraudsters will always seek the weakest point in the hull of a lender’s ship. A unified approach (across channels, products, industries, organisations, regions) ensures that there is no easy entry, and uses all the data and technology at a lender’s disposal to offer maximum protection.

This report will provide statistical models which will prove highly accurate on holdout data, very fast to complete, and run without any errors or warnings, as a way to help organizations fight credit card fraud.

